---
import Layout from '../../../components/layout/Layout.astro';
import ArtworkSchema from '../../../components/seo/ArtworkSchema.astro';

const lang = 'en' as const;
const title = 'Escenas de caza';
---

<Layout
  lang={lang}
  title="Escenas de caza — Work"
  description="Escenas de caza (2000). Installation. VII Havana Biennial. Maria Elvira Escallon."
>

  <ArtworkSchema
    title="Escenas de caza"
    year="2000"
    medium="Installation"
    description="Installation presented at the VII Havana Biennial. Hunting scenes as metaphor."
    url="https://mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/escenas-de-caza/"
  />

  <article class="work-page">
    <div class="container">

      <!-- Header -->
      <header class="work-page__header">
        <p class="label">Work / 025</p>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="work-page__meta">2000 &nbsp;/&nbsp; Installation &nbsp;/&nbsp; VII Havana Biennial</p>
      </header>

      <!-- Main gallery -->
      <div class="work-page__gallery">
        <div class="placeholder-img" style="aspect-ratio: 4/3;">[ Escenas de caza — Images coming soon ]</div>
      </div>

      <!-- Text + Technical sheet -->
      <div class="work-page__body">
        <div class="work-page__text">

          <p class="curatorial">
            <em>Escenas de caza</em> [Hunting Scenes] was presented at the VII Havana
            Biennial in the year 2000. The work addresses hunting scenes as metaphor — the
            pursuit, the prey, the territory, the ritualized violence that the Western
            pictorial tradition has aestheticized for centuries.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            In the Latin American context, the hunting scene acquires particular resonances:
            the conquest, the plundering of territory, the asymmetric relationship between
            the hunter and the hunted. Escallon takes this classic genre of European painting
            and displaces it into the space of installation, activating its connotations of
            power, territory, and violence within a contemporary framework.
          </p>

          <p class="curatorial" style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The Havana Biennial, as a platform for art from the Global South, offered a
            context where these metaphors of hunting and capture dialogued with the
            geopolitical realities shared by the participating countries.
          </p>

          <h3 style="margin-top: var(--s4);">CONTEXT</h3>
          <p style="margin-top: var(--s2);">
            The VII Havana Biennial (2000) was held under the title "Uno mas cerca del otro"
            [One Closer to the Other]. Escallon's participation in this edition marks an
            early moment in her international projection, shortly after the recognition
            gained with <em>In Vitro</em> (1997) and <em>El reino de este mundo</em>
            (1999).
          </p>
        </div>

        <aside class="work-page__ficha">
          <h4>TECHNICAL SHEET</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            <strong>Escenas de caza</strong><br>
            2000<br><br>
            Installation.<br><br>
            Variable dimensions.<br>
            VII Havana Biennial, Cuba.
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">EXHIBITIONS</h4>
          <div class="ficha">
            VII Havana Biennial — Cuba, 2000
          </div>

          <h4 style="margin-top: var(--s3);">HOW TO CITE</h4>
          <div class="ficha" style="font-size: 0.65rem;">
            Escallon, M.E. (2000). <em>Escenas de caza</em>.
            Installation. Available at:
            mariaelviraescallon.com/en/works/escenas-de-caza/
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>

</Layout>
